subsection.md:
\begin{array}{c|c|c}
\text{positive normal direction} \amp \text{ordered tangent directions} \amp \text{oriented area form}\\ \hline
\mathbf i \amp \mathbf j,\mathbf k \amp dy\wedge dz\\[1mm]
\mathbf j \amp \mathbf k,\mathbf i \amp dz\wedge dx\\[1mm]
\mathbf k \amp \mathbf i,\mathbf j \amp dx\wedge dy
\end{array}

\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{field component} \amp \text{oriented coordinate area it crosses} \\ \hline
P \amp dy\wedge dz\\[1mm]
Q \amp dz\wedge dx\\[1mm]
R \amp dx\wedge dy
\end{array}

subsection.p:
For a flux form,

  \boxed{
  \iint_S \Phi_{\mathbf F}
  =
  \iint_S \mathbf F\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}\,dS.
  }

The two notations describe the same signed surface integral.

It says that flux is built from three signed shadows:
\boxed{ \Phi_{\mathbf F} = P\,dy\wedge dz + Q\,dz\wedge dx + R\,dx\wedge dy. }
The P-component crosses yz-area, the Q-component crosses zx-area, and the R-component crosses xy-area.
